      Flash crash
   =20
 =20
If you are a person, and you own 100 shares of Company X stock, and you wan=
t to sell it, one way to do that would be to go to your computer and log in=
to your brokerage=E2=80=99s website=C2=A0and press the button to sell the s=
tock at the market price. That will basically work. If the stock last trade=
d at $100, you will probably sell your stock at a price very close to $100 =
per share, maybe $99.99 or $99.998 or whatever.If you are a trader at a big=
 bank, and you own 100,000 shares of Company X stock, and you want to sell =
it, one way to do that would be to go to your computer and open your tradin=
g program and press the button to sell the stock at the market price. Oops!=
 No, don=E2=80=99t do that. If you do that you might=C2=A0get  stories like=
 this written about you:A sudden selloff in European stock markets just bef=
ore 10 a.m. CET on Monday was fueled by a flash crash in the Nordic region,=
 with traders and fund managers pointing toward a potential portfolio trade=
 error.The OMX Stockholm 30 Index slumped as much as 8% in just five minute=
s before recovering most of the losses shortly after. The index was trading=
 1.1% lower as of 1:00 p.m. CET, roughly in line with a dip in broader mark=
ets.=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s most certainly a =E2=80=98Nordic Flash Crash=E2=
=80=99,=E2=80=9D said Joakim Bornold, savings economist at Soderberg & Part=
ners, adding that equity markets can be very sensitive to erroneous trades =
despite safeguards.While it was not immediately clear what caused the short=
-lived slump, a spokesman for Nasdaq Stockholm said it wasn=E2=80=99t a tec=
hnical glitch on their part. =E2=80=9COur first priority was to exclude tec=
hnical issues in our systems, and our second priority was to exclude an ext=
ernal attack on our systems. We have now excluded both,=E2=80=9D David Augu=
stsson, spokesman for Nasdaq Stockholm, said.=E2=80=9CIt is very clear to u=
s that the cause of this move in the market is a very substantial transacti=
on made by a market participant,=E2=80=9D he said, adding that Nasdaq will =
not cancel any trades made on the Nordic markets.Or  this one:Citigroup Inc=
.=E2=80=99s London trading desk was behind a flash crash that sent shares a=
cross Europe tumbling, dealing a fresh setback to the bank=E2=80=99s yearsl=
ong efforts to improve controls.A trader at the U.S. firm made a mistake =
=E2=80=9Cinputting a transaction,=E2=80=9D Citigroup said late on Monday af=
ter a knee-jerk selloff in Swedish stocks in five minutes wreaked havoc in =
bourses from Paris to Warsaw. The bank said it identified the error =E2=80=
=9Cwithin minutes=E2=80=9D and corrected it.=C2=A0The violent reaction saw =
the main European index lose as much as 3%, wiping out 300 billion euros ($=
315 billion) at one point. It revived questions how large financial firms c=
an prevent such errors, and whether markets have sufficient safeguards in p=
lace.=E2=80=9CThe reality is that, despite all the fancy control systems, l=
arge parts of trading are still manual and human-driven, meaning the =E2=80=
=98fat finger=E2=80=99 isn=E2=80=99t just a metaphor,=E2=80=9D said Oliver =
Scharping, a portfolio manager at Bantleon.I don=E2=80=99t really know what=
 happened here, but I do want to lay out a minimal schematic story of a fla=
sh crash:=09A Citi trader decided to sell large blocks of =E2=80=9Ca basket=
 of shares that included many Swedish names=E2=80=9D for some good reason (=
repositioning a portfolio, hedging some other trade, etc.).=09The trader co=
rrectly typed the names and quantities of stocks to sell=C2=A0into the comp=
uter.=09Then the trader hit the button to sell them.That=E2=80=99s it! I do=
n=E2=80=99t mean to say that that=E2=80=99s what happened here, or that tha=
t=E2=80=99s the=C2=A0only=C2=A0explanation for a flash crash. But the way t=
hat a lot of modern electronic markets work is that if a large trader wants=
 to sell a large position all at once, the market cannot handle it; simply =
sending a single large market order to sell the whole position at once woul=
d be a mistake.=C2=A0We have  talked about this before.=C2=A0The basic idea=
=C2=A0is that modern electronic markets operate on order books that do not =
reflect=C2=A0all=C2=A0of the supply or demand for a stock, or even very muc=
h of it. If you got all the people who trade Nordic stocks together in a bi=
g room =E2=80=94=C2=A0call it=C2=A0a stock exchange =E2=80=94=C2=A0and then=
 a Citi trader walked into the room and said =E2=80=9Chey I want to sell 10=
0,000 shares of these stocks, who wants some,=E2=80=9D enough of them would=
 probably be interested at a price of, say, 1% below the last trade to get =
the deal done.But in modern markets there isn=E2=80=99t a room, and you don=
=E2=80=99t go to all the potential buyers and say =E2=80=9Chey are you inte=
rested?=E2=80=9D Instead, stock exchanges consist of computer programs to m=
atch up buy and sell orders. There will be orders resting on the order book=
 at below the current stock price =E2=80=94=C2=A0some people will put in or=
ders saying =E2=80=9CI would buy some of this stock at 1% below the current=
 price=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0but there won=E2=80=99t be=C2=A0that=C2=A0ma=
ny of them. If you think you would=C2=A0be happy to buy some of the stock a=
t 1% below the current price, you don=E2=80=99t have much of an incentive t=
o put in an order=C2=A0now. You can wait until it drops and then decide. (M=
aybe it dropped for a good reason and you don=E2=80=99t want to buy it anym=
ore.)And so if you come to the exchange with an order to Sell Everything No=
w, the exchange won=E2=80=99t go around polling every potential trader sayi=
ng =E2=80=9Cdo you want to buy this stock?=E2=80=9D Instead it will just lo=
ok at the buy orders already on its book. And if you have a whole lot to se=
ll, you=E2=80=99ll sell to everyone who wanted to buy down 1%, and everyone=
 who wanted to buy down 2%, and so on, until you sell your last shares to p=
eople who wanted to buy down 8%. And then a minute later everyone will noti=
ce that they bought a bunch of stock but that nothing else changed, and so =
they will put in new orders to buy at prices that are slightly below where =
they were two minutes ago, and the stock will rebound almost all the way ba=
ck to where it was before you cleared out the order book with your big trad=
e.This is particularly true if things are otherwise quiet and there=E2=80=
=99s  no one around to buy:Scharping said lower volatility breaks in Nordic=
 markets probably played a role, as did the bank holiday in the U.K., which=
 left European stock markets with about a quarter less liquidity than norma=
l.Again I don=E2=80=99t know if that=E2=80=99s the story=C2=A0here. Other e=
xplanations are possible. Maybe the=C2=A0Citi trader meant to sell 1,000 sh=
ares and accidentally typed in 1,000,000, in a true =E2=80=9Cfat finger=E2=
=80=9D error. Or maybe the Citi trader sold a bunch of shares, and then mom=
entum-following algorithms sold more shares, and then stop-loss orders were=
 triggered forcing more sales, and then margin calls were triggered, etc., =
in a cascade of lower and lower prices.=C2=A0Possible!=E2=80=9CThe problem =
is not the mistake per se, but all the algorithms and stops that were trigg=
ered,=E2=80=9D said John Plassard, a director at Mirabaud & Cie. =E2=80=9CI=
t shows the market is always vulnerable to human error and that algorithms =
and various CTAs are far too present in markets,=E2=80=9D he added, referri=
ng to the commodity trading advisors that often use rapid systematic orders=
 to pursue market trends.=C2=A0And you need some story like that to explain=
 how selling Swedish stocks could cause =E2=80=9Chavoc in bourses from Pari=
s to Warsaw.=E2=80=9D But a basic story of =E2=80=9Cif you try to sell too =
many shares all at once the price will go down=E2=80=9D seems like a decent=
 starting place. =E2=80=9CA very substantial transaction made by a market p=
articipant.=E2=80=9DThis is a story of market fragility, but on the other h=
and it is a small one. The market blipped down and then back up. The error =
wiped =E2=80=9Cout 300 billion euros ($315 billion) at one point=E2=80=9D o=
nly in an abstract sense; the actual amount of stock=C2=A0traded=C2=A0at th=
ose lower prices was relatively=C2=A0small. And it=E2=80=99s a fixable prob=
lem: Banks generally have simple algorithms to do large trades, algorithms =
that space the trade out over a reasonable time, trying to trade, say, 10% =
of volume in any given period until they have sold all the stock they need =
to. If you hit the =E2=80=9CSell Carefully=E2=80=9D button it=E2=80=99s fin=
e. Hitting the =E2=80=9CSell Everything Now=E2=80=9D button is the problem.
