      Always Twitter
   =20
 =20
Elon Musk has  agreed to buy Twitter Inc. for about $46.5 billion, which in=
cludes about $25.5 billion of money borrowed from banks (secured by Twitter=
 and by Musk=E2=80=99s shares of Tesla Inc.) and about $21 billion of equit=
y. Musk himself is on the hook for all of that $21 billion, but he is=C2=A0=
free to syndicate it. If he can find anyone else who wants a piece of Twitt=
er, he=E2=80=99s welcome to sell it to them. He=E2=80=99s trying:Elon Musk =
is in talks with large investment firms and high net-worth individuals abou=
t taking on more financing for his $44 billion acquisition of Twitter Inc. =
and tying up less of his wealth in the deal, people familiar with the matte=
r said. =E2=80=A6The new financing, which could come in the form of preferr=
ed or common equity, could reduce the $21 billion cash contribution that Mu=
sk has committed to the deal as well as a margin loan he secured against hi=
s Tesla shares, the sources said. =E2=80=A6Major investors such as private =
equity firms, hedge funds and high net-worth individuals are in talks with =
Musk about providing preferred equity financing for the acquisition, the so=
urces said. Preferred equity would pay a fixed dividend from Twitter, in th=
e same way that a bond or a loan pays regular interest but would appreciate=
 in line with the equity value of the company. =E2=80=A6Musk has also been =
in talks with some of Twitter's major shareholders about the possibility of=
 them rolling their stake into the deal rather than cashing out, one of the=
 sources said. Former Twitter Chief Executive and current board member Jack=
 Dorsey is examining whether he will roll his take, one source added.Large =
institutional investors, such as Fidelity, are also in talks about rolling =
over their stake, according to the source.Musk has tweeted that he would tr=
y to keep as many investors in Twitter as possible as he takes the company =
private.I don=E2=80=99t really get the preferred equity idea? One problem w=
ith Twitter, as a leveraged-buyout target, is that it doesn=E2=80=99t gener=
ate that much cash. Just paying  the interest bill on the $13 billion that =
of debt that Musk plans to raise against Twitter will be tough with the com=
pany=E2=80=99s cash flow (Bloomberg shows estimated=C2=A02022 earnings befo=
re interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization of $1.57 billion), and he=
 has to pay about another $1 billion on his Tesla margin loans. Preferred s=
tock on Twitter will be junior to the debt, and the unsecured debt that he =
plans to raise on Twitter seems to have an interest rate north of 10%. He=
=E2=80=99s not going to raise billions of dollars of fixed-rate preferred a=
t 15% and then pay out another=C2=A0billion dollars a year to preferred sha=
reholders; that makes no sense.Perhaps he will raise=C2=A0convertible=C2=A0=
preferred, giving some investors an equity=C2=A0claim that is a bit senior =
to his own, without much or any cash dividend. hat makes a bit more sense, =
and is more common in private tech companies. It=E2=80=99s still weird here=
. Twitter is not some startup; if you are a potential investor, you are pro=
bably not=C2=A0that=C2=A0focused on an outcome like =E2=80=9CTwitter is eve=
ntually sold at some price that pays off the debt but doesn=E2=80=99t fully=
 return Musk=E2=80=99s investment.=E2=80=9D (In which case=C2=A0a convertib=
le preferred would be valuable.) Who would buy Twitter from Musk? Why would=
 he sell it? I don=E2=80=99t know.Meanwhile the rollover equity idea is a l=
ong-standing dream of Musk=E2=80=99s. It=E2=80=99s  what he wanted with Tes=
la, back when he pretended he would take it private in 2018. The dream, for=
 a lot of visionary tech startup founders, is:=09Raise a lot of money from =
the deep liquid public capital markets, selling stock to giant institutions=
 like Fidelity and also enthusiastic retail investors.[1]=09Keep total cont=
rol of your company and not have to listen to shareholders.=09Get to choose=
 your shareholders, so you can exclude annoying ones.=09Ban short selling.=
=09Not have a stock price that changes every day and makes you feel bad whe=
n it goes down.You can get some of these things in the public markets (dual=
-class stock mostly lets you keep control while raising public money), and =
you can get a lot of them in the private markets (all of them, really, exce=
pt No. 1, and the private markets are pretty big and liquid these days), bu=
t I suppose you can always try to tweak it a little. Taking an existing pub=
lic company and making it private while keeping a lot of the shareholders i=
s one way to achieve the dream.There is something a little weird, though,=
=C2=A0about broadly marketing rollover equity in Musk Twitter to shareholde=
rs of Existing Twitter. Eventually there is going to be a proxy statement f=
or this merger, and in effect Twitter=E2=80=99s board  will say to sharehol=
ders =E2=80=9Cyou should take this deal because $54.20 in cash is more than=
 Twitter=E2=80=99s stock is worth.=E2=80=9D Meanwhile Musk is going out to =
potential equity investors and saying the opposite: =E2=80=9CChip in some m=
oney because this thing is worth more than $54.20.=E2=80=9D If a select few=
 of Twitter=E2=80=99s existing big shareholders =E2=80=94 perhaps=C2=A0incl=
uding Jack Dorsey, a=C2=A0board member who ran Twitter for years and voted =
for the deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0are offered the chance to stick around, and tak=
e it, then that undermines the logic of the deal. =E2=80=9CElon Musk can ma=
ke Twitter vastly more valuable than $54.20 per share, but not for you=E2=
=80=9D is not a great message for the board to send to most of its sharehol=
ders.Meanwhile, Twitter filed a Form 10-Q with new risk factors about how t=
he deal with Musk  might undermine its business:Twitter Inc.=E2=80=99s $44 =
billion deal to be acquired by Elon Musk means it risks losing advertisers =
and employees, who may be concerned about the company=E2=80=99s uncertain f=
uture.Twitter said it may be difficult to attract and retain key people, an=
d mentioned =E2=80=9Cthe possibility that our current employees could be di=
stracted, and their productivity decline as a result, due to uncertainty re=
garding the merger,=E2=80=9D the company said in a regulatory filing Monday=
.In a sense, this doesn=E2=80=99t matter: As long as the deal closes, Twitt=
er=E2=80=99s shareholders have no reason to care about employee retention o=
r advertisers; they just get cashed out at $54.20 per share, and all this s=
tuff is Musk=E2=80=99s problem. But of course if the deal=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=
=99t close then it=E2=80=99s the shareholders=E2=80=99 problem.
 =20
   =20
      Insider trading
   =20
 =20
One misconception that people have about insider trading is that, to be gui=
lty of insider trading in a company=E2=80=99s stock, you need to have insid=
e information about the company. This is not true. Insider trading is, more=
 or less, a crime of trading on misappropriated=C2=A0information. If you kn=
ow something that is=C2=A0material to the stock, and you have some duty to =
keep that information confidential and not use it for yourself, then tradin=
g on it is insider trading.So, for instance, if a newspaper publishes a sto=
ck-picking column, and you get the column before it is published and buy th=
e stocks it recommends, that is famously insider trading even if the column=
ist has no inside information about the companies. (It=E2=80=99s insider tr=
ading even if you are the columnist.) It=E2=80=99s not that you knew inside=
 information about the company; it=E2=80=99s that you had information (1) t=
hat you weren=E2=80=99t supposed to have (or at least that you weren=E2=80=
=99t supposed to trade on) and (2) that moved the stock price.Or if you wor=
k at a company and get news about a merger and  buy your=C2=A0competitor=E2=
=80=99s=C2=A0stock, figuring that your competitor=E2=80=99s stock will go u=
p on your merger news, that is also (arguably!) insider trading: You had in=
formation (about your company), you weren=E2=80=99t supposed to trade on it=
 (under your company=E2=80=99s policies), and it was material=C2=A0to your =
competitor, in the simple sense that when the news came out the competitor=
=E2=80=99s stock went up.Or if you hack into the computer systems of=C2=A0a=
 stock-picks newsletter and buy the stocks it is going to pick, you might n=
ot=C2=A0think=C2=A0that=E2=80=99s insider trading, but the Justice Departme=
nt and Securities and Exchange Commission will. Here=E2=80=99s an email tha=
t David Stone allegedly sent to a buddy:I'm ok with sharing the weekly trad=
es with you. I have used it so far to generate a significant amount of mone=
y and I'm sure you will be able to as well. There is a small possibility th=
at what we are doing could be considered insider trading. [Advisor-1] uses =
only public information about to make its recommendations and even the reco=
mmendations are behind a paywall so it is a stretch to call it insider trad=
ing but it certainly behaves like it because it almost guarantees favorable=
 price moves at a certain time.=C2=A0And here is the Justice Department pre=
ss release:Damian Williams, the United States Attorney for the Southern Dis=
trict of New York, and Michael J. Driscoll, Assistant Director-in-Charge of=
 the New York Field Office of the Federal Bureau of Investigation (=E2=80=
=9CFBI=E2=80=9D), announced today the unsealing of a complaint charging DAV=
ID STONE with securities fraud in connection with an insider trading scheme=
. STONE was arrested yesterday and will be presented today in the United St=
ates District Court for the District of Oregon. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0From 2020 up=
 to his arrest in 2022, DAVID STONE exploited market-moving stock recommend=
ations made by an investment recommendation service (=E2=80=9CAdvisor-1=E2=
=80=9D) before those recommendations were released to paying subscribers. S=
TONE, an information technology (=E2=80=9CI.T.=E2=80=9D) professional, acce=
ssed Advisor-1=E2=80=99s computing system without authorization and viewed =
information relating to Advisor-1=E2=80=99s recommendations before they wer=
e announced to Advisor-1=E2=80=99s paying subscribers.Advisor-1=E2=80=99s s=
tock recommendations typically, but not always, lead to higher closing pric=
es for the recommended stock as compared to the prior day=E2=80=99s closing=
 price. By trading on those recommendations before they were announced, STO=
NE was able to obtain significant profits unavailable to other market parti=
cipants. In fact, since in or about November 2020, brokerage accounts assoc=
iated with STONE traded ahead of Advisor-1 recommendations on more than a d=
ozen occasions for approximately $3 million in gross gains.I don=E2=80=99t =
know who Advisor-1 is. I will say that the limit case here is if you hack i=
nto a pure pump-and-dump email list, someone who pumps stocks to a subscrib=
er list based on no information or analysis at all but just to run a scam, =
and you buy the stocks he=E2=80=99s going to pump before he pumps them, the=
n I think that is probably also insider trading? The point is the misapprop=
riation and the materiality, not the quality of the information.
 =20
   =20
      The wrong Ma
   =20
 =20
Speaking of information that is material to a company without being=C2=A0ab=
out=C2=A0that company:Alibaba shares sold off on Tuesday following a Chines=
e state media report that an individual surnamed =E2=80=9CMa=E2=80=9D had b=
een detained, pushing down Chinese technology stocks that had been expected=
 to rally on the promise of support from Beijing.Shares in the Chinese ecom=
merce giant fell as much as 9.4 per cent at the open in Hong Kong following=
 the report. The shares later pulled back to be down about 1 per cent after=
 China=E2=80=99s state broadcaster CCTV amended its one-sentence dispatch t=
o indicate the individual was not Alibaba=E2=80=99s billionaire founder Jac=
k Ma.If you knew about the other Ma=E2=80=99s arrest in advance and you sho=
rted Alibaba=E2=80=99s stock, etc.
