om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Flash crash</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a person, and you own 100 s=
hares of Company X stock, and you want to sell it, one way to do that would=
 be to go to your computer and log into your brokerage=E2=80=99s website=C2=
=A0and press the button to sell the stock at the market price. That will ba=
sically work. If the stock last traded at $100, you will probably sell your=
 stock at a price very close to $100 per share, maybe $99.99 or $99.998 or =
whatever.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a trader at a big bank=
, and you own 100,000 shares of Company X stock, and you want to sell it, o=
ne way to do that would be to go to your computer and open your trading pro=
gram and press the button to sell the stock at the market price. Oops! No, =
don=E2=80=99t do that. If you do that you might=C2=A0get <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27582995.270604/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxv=
b21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMDIvY2l0aS1zLWxvbmRvbi10cmFkaW5=
nLWRlc2stYmVoaW5kLXJhcmUtZXVyb3BlYW4tZmxhc2gtY3Jhc2g_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUwMzIyX0=
1PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlc=
m09MjIwNTAzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB52c30c=
c2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> stories like this</a> written about you:</p><blockquote><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A sudden selloff in European stock markets just bef=
ore 10 a.m. CET on Monday was fueled by a flash crash in the Nordic region,=
 with traders and fund managers pointing toward a potential portfolio trade=
 error.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The OMX Stockholm 30 Index slumped =
as much as 8% in just five minutes before recovering most of the losses sho=
rtly after. The index was trading 1.1% lower as of 1:00 p.m. CET, roughly i=
n line with a dip in broader markets.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=
=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s most certainly a =E2=80=98Nordic Flash Crash=E2=80=99,=
=E2=80=9D said Joakim Bornold, savings economist at Soderberg &amp; Partner=
s, adding that equity markets can be very sensitive to erroneous trades des=
pite safeguards.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While it was not immediate=
ly clear what caused the short-lived slump, a spokesman for Nasdaq Stockhol=
m said it wasn=E2=80=99t a technical glitch on their part. =E2=80=9COur fir=
st priority was to exclude technical issues in our systems, and our second =
priority was to exclude an external attack on our systems. We have now excl=
uded both,=E2=80=9D David Augustsson, spokesman for Nasdaq Stockholm, said.=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIt is very clear to us that the c=
ause of this move in the market is a very substantial transaction made by a=
 market participant,=E2=80=9D he said, adding that Nasdaq will not cancel a=
ny trades made on the Nordic markets.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">Or <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2758299=
5.270604/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMD=
IvY2l0aS1zLWxvbmRvbi10cmFkaW5nLWRlc2stYmVoaW5kLXJhcmUtZXVyb3BlYW4tZmxhc2gtY=
3Jhc2g_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUwMzIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291=
cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNTAzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC52c30cc2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> this one</a>:</p><blockquote><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Citigroup Inc.=E2=80=99s London trading desk was b=
ehind a flash crash that sent shares across Europe tumbling, dealing a fres=
h setback to the bank=E2=80=99s yearslong efforts to improve controls.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A trader at the U.S. firm made a mistake =E2=80=
=9Cinputting a transaction,=E2=80=9D Citigroup said late on Monday after a =
knee-jerk selloff in Swedish stocks in five minutes wreaked havoc in bourse=
s from Paris to Warsaw. The bank said it identified the error =E2=80=9Cwith=
in minutes=E2=80=9D and corrected it.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>The violent reaction saw the main European index lose as much as 3%, wipin=
g out 300 billion euros ($315 billion) at one point. It revived questions h=
ow large financial firms can prevent such errors, and whether markets have =
sufficient safeguards in place.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CTh=
e reality is that, despite all the fancy control systems, large parts of tr=
ading are still manual and human-driven, meaning the =E2=80=98fat finger=E2=
=80=99 isn=E2=80=99t just a metaphor,=E2=80=9D said Oliver Scharping, a por=
tfolio manager at Bantleon.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I =
don=E2=80=99t really know what happened here, but I do want to lay out a mi=
nimal schematic story of a flash crash:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: de=
cimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: =
5px;">A Citi trader decided to sell large blocks of =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27582995.270604/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
ZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvNjViMmUzNGUtM2IzMC00ZjFkLWFkNTktNjdmOWQ5MWQ4M2E0/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cBdd29233a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">a basket of shares</a> that included m=
any Swedish names=E2=80=9D for some good reason (repositioning a portfolio,=
 hedging some other trade, etc.).</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=
The trader correctly typed the names and quantities of stocks to sell=C2=A0=
into the computer.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Then the trader=
 hit the button to sell them.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=
=80=99s it! I don=E2=80=99t mean to say that that=E2=80=99s what happened h=
ere, or that that=E2=80=99s the=C2=A0<em>only=C2=A0</em>explanation for a f=
lash crash. But the way that a lot of modern electronic markets work is tha=
t if a large trader wants to sell a large position all at once, the market =
cannot handle it; simply sending a single large market order to sell the wh=
ole position at once would be a mistake.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">We have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/275829=
95.270604/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktM=
DEtMDMvdGhlLWNvbXB1dGVycy1hcmUtc29ycnktYWJvdXQtdGhlLWZsYXNoLWNyYXNoZXM_Y21w=
aWQ9QkJEMDUwMzIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3N=
sZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNTAzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB9a123a8a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked about this before</a>.=C2=A0The basic=
 idea=C2=A0is that modern electronic markets operate on order books that do=
 not reflect=C2=A0<em>all=C2=A0</em>of the supply or demand for a stock, or=
 even very much of it. If you got all the people who trade Nordic stocks to=
gether in a big room =E2=80=94=C2=A0call it=C2=A0a stock exchange =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0and then a Citi trader walked into the room and said =E2=80=9Chey I w=
ant to sell 100,000 shares of these stocks, who wants some,=E2=80=9D enough=
 of them would probably be interested at a price of, say, 1% below the last=
 trade to get the deal done.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in modern =
markets there isn=E2=80=99t a room, and you don=E2=80=99t go to all the pot=
ential buyers and say =E2=80=9Chey are you interested?=E2=80=9D Instead, st=
ock exchanges consist of computer programs to match up buy and sell orders.=
 There will be orders resting on the order book at below the current stock =
price =E2=80=94=C2=A0some people will put in orders saying =E2=80=9CI would=
 buy some of this stock at 1% below the current price=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0but there won=E2=80=99t be=C2=A0<em>that=C2=A0</em>many of them. If you =
think you would=C2=A0be happy to buy some of the stock at 1% below the curr=
ent price, you don=E2=80=99t have much of an incentive to put in an order=
=C2=A0<em>now</em>. You can wait until it drops and then decide. (Maybe it =
dropped for a good reason and you don=E2=80=99t want to buy it anymore.)</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so if you come to the exchange with an or=
der to Sell Everything Now, the exchange won=E2=80=99t go around polling ev=
ery potential trader saying =E2=80=9Cdo you want to buy this stock?=E2=80=
=9D Instead it will just look at the buy orders already on its book. And if=
 you have a whole lot to sell, you=E2=80=99ll sell to everyone who wanted t=
o buy down 1%, and everyone who wanted to buy down 2%, and so on, until you=
 sell your last shares to people who wanted to buy down 8%. And then a minu=
te later everyone will notice that they bought a bunch of stock but that no=
thing else changed, and so they will put in new orders to buy at prices tha=
t are slightly below where they were two minutes ago, and the stock will re=
bound almost all the way back to where it was before you cleared out the or=
der book with your big trade.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is parti=
cularly true if things are otherwise quiet and there=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27582995.270604/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMDIvY2l0aS1zLWxvbmRvbi10c=
mFkaW5nLWRlc2stYmVoaW5kLXJhcmUtZXVyb3BlYW4tZmxhc2gtY3Jhc2g_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUw=
MzIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXR=
tX3Rlcm09MjIwNTAzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cD=
52c30cc2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;"> no one around to buy</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">Scharping said lower volatility breaks in Nordic markets prob=
ably played a role, as did the bank holiday in the U.K., which left Europea=
n stock markets with about a quarter less liquidity than normal.</p></block=
quote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Again I don=E2=80=99t know if that=E2=80=
=99s the story=C2=A0here. Other explanations are possible. Maybe the=C2=A0C=
iti trader meant to sell 1,000 shares and accidentally typed in 1,000,000, =
in a true =E2=80=9Cfat finger=E2=80=9D error. Or maybe the Citi trader sold=
 a bunch of shares, and then momentum-following algorithms sold more shares=
, and then stop-loss orders were triggered forcing more sales, and then mar=
gin calls were triggered, etc., in a cascade of lower and lower prices.=C2=
=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27582995.270604=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMDMvY2l0aS=
1zLXBhaW5mdWwtZmxhc2gtY3Jhc2gtaGlnaGxpZ2h0cy1tYXJrZXQtcmlza3MtZnJvbS1hbGdvc=
z9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTAzMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9=
bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA1MDMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB5f9232d8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Possible</a>!</p><blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe problem is not the mistake per se, but al=
l the algorithms and stops that were triggered,=E2=80=9D said John Plassard=
, a director at Mirabaud &amp; Cie. =E2=80=9CIt shows the market is always =
vulnerable to human error and that algorithms and various CTAs are far too =
present in markets,=E2=80=9D he added, referring to the commodity trading a=
dvisors that often use rapid systematic orders to pursue market trends.=C2=
=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And you need some story li=
ke that to explain how selling Swedish stocks could cause =E2=80=9Chavoc in=
 bourses from Paris to Warsaw.=E2=80=9D But a basic story of =E2=80=9Cif yo=
u try to sell too many shares all at once the price will go down=E2=80=9D s=
eems like a decent starting place. =E2=80=9CA very substantial transaction =
made by a market participant.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This=
 is a story of market fragility, but on the other hand it is a small one. T=
he market blipped down and then back up. The error wiped =E2=80=9Cout 300 b=
illion euros ($315 billion) at one point=E2=80=9D only in an abstract sense=
; the actual amount of stock=C2=A0<em>traded=C2=A0</em>at those lower price=
s was relatively=C2=A0small. And it=E2=80=99s a fixable problem: Banks gene=
rally have simple algorithms to do large trades, algorithms that space the =
trade out over a reasonable time, trying to trade, say, 10% of volume in an=
y given period until they have sold all the stock they need to. If you hit =
the =E2=80=9CSell Carefully=E2=80=9D button it=E2=80=99s fine. Hitting the =
=E2=80=9CSell Everything Now=E2=80=9D button is the problem.</p><table clas=
s=3D"liveintent-sponsored-content" width=3D"auto" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspa=
cing=3D"0">
